SYPHILIS - USA (12): (CALIFORNIA) MEN WHO HAVE SEX WITH MEN, WOMEN, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*******************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 2 Sep 2015
Source: Paradise Post [edited]
http://www.paradisepost.com/general-news/20150902/lab-confirmed-syphilis-on-the-rise-in-butte-county


The Butte County [California] Public Health Department [BCPHD] announced on Wednesday [2 Sep 2015] that there's been a major increase this year in lab confirmed cases of the sexually transmitted disease syphilis. The county says that from January to June [2015], there have been 12 confirmed syphilis cases reported, compared to only 2 cases in 2014 during the same time period.

The county also said that people between 20-29 years old and 40-54 years old have been affected, and 1/3rd of those cases occurred in women. The remaining cases, the county said, were found in men who have sex with men (MSM) and in heterosexual males.

Syphilis is a bacterial infection spread through sexual contact, including oral, vaginal and anal sex, with an infected person. The disease is known as "The Great Imitator" because syphilis symptoms can look like symptoms from other diseases.

Syphilis develops in stages and symptoms vary with each stage. The most common symptoms include: small ulcers on the genitals, rectum or mouth, and a non-itchy body rash on the palms of hands or soles of feet, often mistaken as a skin reaction or condition. Stages may overlap and don't always occur in the same order. You may be infected with syphilis and not notice any symptoms for years. If left untreated, syphilis can cause permanent health problems, including blindness and damage to the heart, brain and spinal cord. Pregnant women infected with syphilis may pass the bacteria to their baby during childbirth, which may cause severe birth defects and health issues that may not show up for years after birth.

"Testing and treatment for syphilis is quick and simple. We urge people at risk to get tested often, as symptoms may be hard to recognize" states Butte County Health Officer, Dr. Mark Lundberg.

Increases in syphilis throughout Butte County are consistent with statewide trends. The California Department of Public Health is reporting an increase in ocular (infection of the eye) syphilis.

BCPHD says that if you are sexually active, your chances of getting syphilis may be reduced by being in a monogamous relationship, limiting sex partners and using a latex condom every time you have sex. Free condoms and free or low-cost STD testing are available at BCPHD clinics in both Chico and Oroville. For more information or to make an appointment please call 891-2731 in Chico or 538-7341 in Oroville. Additional locations throughout Butte County offer free condoms.

[Byline: Rick Silva]

