[The state of California can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3622699,2116. Butte County, in the Central Valley of California, can be seen on the map at http://geology.com/county-map/california-county-map.gif; it is rural and agricultural (http://www.buttegeneralplan.net/products/SettingandTrends/01_LandUse.pdf), with a population (in 2010) of 220 000 (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Butte_County,_California#Demographics). The city of Chico, Butte County's largest urban community with a total population (in 2010) of 86 187, is home to a major California State University campus with about 16 500 college students. Chico is located in the northwest part of Butte County, about 85 miles (137 km), via California State Route 99, north of the nearest large metropolis, the city of Sacramento, the California state capital.

ProMED-mail posted a report of an outbreak of syphilis in the 1st quarter of 2013 in Butte in young men who had sex with men (MSM) with multiple sexual contacts, "many" of whom were anonymous (ProMED-mail post Syphilis - USA: (CA) MSM, RFI 20130522.1730900). Butte County had reported only one case in the period 2006 to 2011 of primary or secondary syphilis in 2009 (http://www.cdph.ca.gov/data/statistics/Documents/STD-Data-2010-Report.pdf) and 2 cases in 2011 (http://www.cdph.ca.gov/data/statistics/Documents/STD-Data-LHJ-Butte.pdf). We were not told if the syphilis cases were college students or where syphilis was acquired, in Butte County or in Sacramento, the nearest large metropolis.

In 2015, ProMED-mail reported that about half of those with gonococcal disease were between 14 and 25 years old and because of their age the report suggests that they may be Chico State students. However, the news report failed to describe the cases in further detail, such as their sexual behavior or use of smartphone apps, drugs, etc., which would be needed to plan an effective prevention program that targets specific characteristics driving the outbreak in Butte County.

The 2015 news report above says that people between 20-29 years old and 40-54 years old have developed syphilis, and 1/3rd of the cases occurred in women. The remaining cases were men who have sex with men (MSM) and heterosexual males. We again were not told if the syphilis cases were college students or where syphilis was acquired, in Butte County or in Sacramento; whether any had HIV infection; used smartphone apps for "hook-ups," or used psychoactive drugs.

More information on this outbreak of STDs in Butte County from knowledgeable sources would be greatly appreciated. - Mod.ML]
